<CaseStudy slug="operation-hired">
  <p class="lead reveal">Job searching now means wading through thousands of postings, most of them irrelevant and a fair number fake. I built Operation Hired to deal with that. It pulls postings in, scores them, and ranks them, so I only spend time on the ones worth a look.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">What it does</h2>
  <p class="reveal">Postings land in a local <code>SQLite</code> database, each one runs through a scoring model, and the result is a ranked shortlist. So far it has scored <strong>5,905</strong> of them, and every score can be reproduced from the source data. The ranking is the easy part. The real work went into making that ranking something I could trust.</p>

  <h2 class="reveal">How the scoring works</h2>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li><strong>Tiering.</strong> Postings get bucketed by fit (role, seniority, pay signal). An early version was too generous with the top bucket, so I tightened it. The "tier 1" count dropped from a few thousand to about a hundred, which is what real fit should look like.</li>
    <li><strong>Geo-matching.</strong> Location gets checked against where I can actually work, so remote-mislabeled and wrong-city postings stop polluting the list.</li>
    <li><strong>Fraud signals.</strong> A set of heuristics flags the patterns ghost and scam listings tend to share. That cut the flagged-fraud noise by about 80%.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Built so I can trust it</h2>
  <p class="reveal">The system treats its own data as something to audit, not something to assume:</p>
  <ul class="reveal">
    <li>A <strong>re-score pipeline</strong> re-ran all 5,905 rows against the corrected model in one pass with <strong>zero errors</strong>, after backing up first.</li>
    <li>A <strong>95-case test suite</strong> covers the scoring edges, the geo logic, and the fraud heuristics. It's green before anything ships.</li>
    <li><strong>Data-hygiene guards</strong> clear out orphaned stress-test rows and stop half-formed records from moving down the pipeline.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="reveal">Why I point to this one</h2>
  <p class="reveal">It's a small but real example of how I work: a pipeline that makes a lot of decisions, knows where it might be wrong, and checks itself with tests and repeatable re-runs. I'd rather show evidence than make claims, and that holds for everything I build.</p>
</CaseStudy>
